  "why": "TESTRNN enforces semantic consistency and realistic (natural) mutations in ways that preserve semantics for discrete domains (text via EDA mutations; SMILES enumeration preserves molecular structure) and uses small Gaussian noise for continuous inputs, and it also tracks each mutant's original seed (orig mapping). However, the paper does not describe mechanisms that constrain cumulative distortion relative to the original seed across multiple mutation iterations (mutations are applied to selected mutants/parents and can accumulate), nor does it enforce an explicit global similarity bound to the original seed across generations. Thus plausibility/naturalness and semantic preservation are enforced between successive mutation steps (and by per-mutation design) but the design does not account for potential cumulative drift across iterative mutations.",
  "evidence": "Page 1, Abstract: \"...and the consideration of the naturalness of input perturbation.\" (Abstract)\n\nPage 7 (Section VI, Algorithm 1 / Selection & mutation descriptions): \"it keeps the traceability of test cases via a mapping orig that maps each test case generated back to its seed origin.\" and Algorithm 1 shows orig[x'] <- orig[x]. (Alg. 1 and accompanying text)\n\nPage 6 (VI.B.1 Random Mutation): \"When the LSTM input has continuous values (e.g., image input), Gaussian noises with fixed mean and variance are added to the input.\" (Section VI-B.1, p.1196)\n\nPage 10 (VII-A.3 Input Mutation; experimental setup): \"The input to IMDB model is a sequence of words, on which a random change may lead to an unrecognizable (and invalid) text paragraph. To avoid this, we take a set M of mutants from the EDA toolkit ..., This ensures the mutated text paragraphs are always valid. In our experiments, we consider four mutation operations, i.e., M includes synonym replacement, random insertion, random swap, and random deletion. The text meanings are reserved in all mutations.\" (Section VII-A.3, p.1200)\n\nPage 10 (VII-A.3, Lipophilicity): \"For Lipophilicity model, we take a set M of mutants that change the SMILES string without affecting the molecular structure it represents. The enumeration of possible SMILES for a molecule is implemented with the Python cheminformatics package RDkit.\" (Section VII-A.3, p.1200)\n\nPage 7–8 (VI.C Test Oracle): \"We define a set of norm-balls, each of which is centered around a data sample with known label. The radius r_oracle of norm-balls intuitively means that a human cannot differentiate between inputs within a norm ball... Euclidean distance, i.e., L2-norm ||·||2 is used... A test case x' is said to not pass the oracle if x' is within the norm-ball of some known sample x, i.e., ||x - x'||2 ≤ r_oracle, and if x' has a different classification from x.\" (Section VI-C.1, p.1198)\n\nPage 6 (VI.B.2 Targeted Mutation): description of genetic search where parents (mutants) are selected and mutated iteratively (\"We randomly mutate the test cases in the mating pool with user-defined function M... The previous population is replaced with the new one. The parents in the mating pool are also added to the new population...\") — showing iterative mutation on mutants rather than enforcing a bound to the original seed. (Section VI-B.2, p.1196–1197)\n\nNote: while per-mutation operations are designed to preserve semantics/naturalness (EDA for text, SMILES enumeration for molecules, small Gaussian noise for images), the paper does not describe safeguards that prevent cumulative distortion across many mutation iterations (no explicit cumulative similarity constraint to original seed is stated)."
